Adult/immature.description: Willow Flycatchers have greener heads and upperparts, paler sides, and wider and whiter wing bars (at least in adults) than Eastern Wood-Pewees. They do not tend to sally and return to the same perch like pewees.
Acadian Flycatchers usually have an obvious white eyering that Eastern Wood-Pewees do not have and they have a paler belly.
Eastern Phoebes have darker brown upperparts and no wingbars while Eastern Wood-Pewees are grayer with grayish wingbars. Their underparts tend to be cleaner white, without a vested look.

Adult.description: Olive-sided Flycatchers are larger, with a larger head and a thicker and longer bill than Eastern Wood-Pewees.

Adult/immature.description: Western Wood-Pewees look nearly identical to Eastern Wood-Pewees, but their breeding ranges hardly overlap and their calls are different, the best way to separate them.
